# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: industry-4-0
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:industry-4-0/additive-manufacturing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data analysis challenges include capturing data, data storage, data analysis, search, sharing, transfer, visualization, querying, updating, information privacy, and data sources.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data was originally associated with three key concepts: *volume*, *variety*, and *velocity*.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The analysis of big data that have only volume, velocity, and variety can pose challenges in sampling.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] A fourth concept, *veracity,* which refers to the level of reliability of data, was thus added.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Current usage of the term *big data* tends to refer to the use of predictive analytics, user behavior analytics, or certain other advanced data analytics methods that extract value from big data, and seldom to a particular size of data set.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] "There is little doubt that the quantities of data now available are indeed large, but that's not the most relevant characteristic of this new data ecosystem." Analysis of data sets can find new correlations to "spot business trends, prevent diseases, combat crime and so on".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Scientists, business executives, medical practitioners, advertising and governments alike regularly meet difficulties with large datasets in areas including Internet searches, fintech, healthcare analytics, geographic information systems, urban informatics, and business informatics.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Scientists encounter limitations in e-Science work, including meteorology, genomics, connectomics, complex physics simulations, biology, and environmental research.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The world's technological per-capita capacity to store information has roughly doubled every 40 months since the 1980s; as of 2012, every day 2.5 exabytes (2.17×260 bytes) of data are generated.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Based on an IDC report prediction, the global data volume was predicted to grow exponentially from 4.4 zettabytes to 44 zettabytes between 2013 and 2020.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] By 2025, IDC predicts there will be 163 zettabytes of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] According to IDC, global spending on big data and business analytics (BDA) solutions is estimated to reach $215.7 billion in 2021.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Statista reported that the global big data market is forecasted to grow to $103 billion by 2027.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In 2011 McKinsey & Company reported, if US healthcare were to use big data creatively and effectively to drive efficiency and quality, the sector could create more than $300 billion in value every year.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In the developed economies of Europe, government administrators could save more than €100 billion ($149 billion) in operational efficiency improvements alone by using big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] And users of services enabled by personal-location data could capture $600 billion in consumer surplus.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] One question for large enterprises is determining who should own big-data initiatives that affect the entire organization.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Relational database management systems and desktop statistical software packages used to visualize data often have difficulty processing and analyzing big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The processing and analysis of big data may require "massively parallel software running on tens, hundreds, or even thousands of servers".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] What qualifies as "big data" varies depending on the capabilities of those analyzing it and their tools.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Furthermore, expanding capabilities make big data a moving target.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] "For some organizations, facing hundreds of gigabytes of data for the first time may trigger a need to reconsider data management options.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The term *big data* has been in use since the 1990s, with some giving credit to John Mashey for popularizing the term.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data usually includes data sets with sizes beyond the ability of commonly used software tools to capture, curate, manage, and process data within a tolerable elapsed time.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data philosophy encompasses unstructured, semi-structured and structured data; however, the main focus is on unstructured data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data "size" is a constantly moving target; as of 2012 ranging from a few dozen terabytes to many zettabytes of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data requires a set of techniques and technologies with new forms of integration to reveal insights from datasets that are diverse, complex, and of a massive scale.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Variability is often included as an additional quality of big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In a comparative study of big datasets, Kitchin and McArdle found that none of the commonly considered characteristics of big data appear consistently across all of the analyzed cases.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] For this reason, other studies identified the redefinition of power dynamics in knowledge discovery as the defining trait.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Instead of focusing on the intrinsic characteristics of big data, this alternative perspective pushes forward a relational understanding of the object claiming that what matters is the way in which data is collected, stored, made available and analyzed.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The quantity of generated and stored data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The size of the data determines the value and potential insight, and whether it can be considered big data or not.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The size of big data is usually larger than terabytes and petabytes.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Earlier technologies like RDBMSs were capable to handle structured data efficiently and effectively.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] However, the change in type and nature from structured to semi-structured or unstructured challenged the existing tools and technologies.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data technologies evolved with the prime intention to capture, store, and process the semi-structured and unstructured (variety) data generated with high speed (velocity), and huge in size (volume).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Later, these tools and technologies were explored and used for handling structured data also but preferable for storage.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Eventually, the processing of structured data was still kept as optional, either using big data or traditional RDBMSs.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This helps in analyzing data towards effective usage of the hidden insights exposed from the data collected via social media, log files, sensors, etc.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The speed at which the data is generated and processed to meet the demands and challenges that lie in the path of growth and development.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data is often available in real-time.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] , big data is produced more continually.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Two kinds of velocity related to big data are the frequency of generation and the frequency of handling, recording, and publishing.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The truthfulness or reliability of the data, which refers to the data quality and the data value.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data must not only be large in size, but also must be reliable in order to achieve value in the analysis of it.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] of captured data can vary greatly, affecting an accurate analysis.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The worth in information that can be achieved by the processing and analysis of large datasets.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Value also can be measured by an assessment of the other qualities of big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Value may also represent the profitability of information that is retrieved from the analysis of big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Unlike variety, variability captures the notion the fact that formats, structure, or sources of big data change through time and given different circumstances.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Interpretation of data depends on a changing context, and with a different context, the old meanings may become invalid.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data may or may not include all the available data from sources.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Respectively, the proportion of specific data of each element per element collected and if the element and its characteristics are properly indexed or identified.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] If the data collected contains common fields that would enable a conjoining, or meta-analysis, of different data sets.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] If new fields in each element of the data collected can be added or changed easily.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] If the size of the big data storage system can expand rapidly.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data repositories have existed in many forms, often built by corporations with a special need.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Commercial vendors historically offered parallel database management systems for big data beginning in the 1990s.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] For many years, WinterCorp published the largest database report.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Teradata Corporation in 1984 marketed the parallel processing DBC 1012 system.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Teradata systems were the first to store and analyze 1 terabyte of data in 1992.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Hard disk drives were 2.5 GB in 1991 so the definition of big data continuously evolves.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Teradata installed the first petabyte class RDBMS based system in 2007.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] As of 2017, there are a few dozen petabyte class Teradata relational databases installed, the largest of which exceeds 50 PB.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Systems up until 2008 were 100% structured relational data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Since then, Teradata has added semi structured data types including XML, JSON, and Avro.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] (now LexisNexis Risk Solutions) developed a C++-based distributed platform for data processing and querying known as the HPCC Systems platform.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This system automatically partitions, distributes, stores and delivers structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data across multiple commodity servers.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Users can write data processing pipelines and queries in a declarative dataflow programming language called ECL.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Data analysts working in ECL are not required to define data schemas upfront and can rather focus on the particular problem at hand, reshaping data in the best possible manner as they develop the solution.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In 2004, LexisNexis acquired Seisint Inc. and their high-speed parallel processing platform and successfully used this platform to integrate the data systems of Choicepoint Inc. when they acquired that company in 2008.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In 2011, the HPCC systems platform was open-sourced under the Apache v2.0 License.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] CERN and other physics experiments have collected big data sets for many decades, usually analyzed via high-throughput computing rather than the map-reduce architectures usually meant by the current "big data" movement.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In 2004, Google published a paper on a process called MapReduce that uses a similar architecture.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The MapReduce concept provides a parallel processing model, and an associated implementation was released to process huge amounts of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] With MapReduce, queries are split and distributed across parallel nodes and processed in parallel (the "map" step).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The results are then gathered and delivered (the "reduce" step).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The framework was very successful, so others wanted to replicate the algorithm.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Therefore, an implementation of the MapReduce framework was adopted by an Apache open-source project named "Hadoop".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Apache Spark was developed in 2012 in response to limitations in the MapReduce paradigm, as it adds in-memory processing and the ability to set up many operations (not just map followed by reducing).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] MIKE2.0 is an open approach to information management that acknowledges the need for revisions due to big data implications identified in an article titled "Big Data Solution Offering".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The methodology addresses handling big data in terms of useful permutations of data sources, complexity in interrelationships, and difficulty in deleting (or modifying) individual records.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Studies in 2012 showed that a multiple-layer architecture was one option to address the issues that big data presents.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] A distributed parallel architecture distributes data across multiple servers; these parallel execution environments can dramatically improve data processing speeds.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This type of architecture inserts data into a parallel DBMS, which implements the use of MapReduce and Hadoop frameworks.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This type of framework looks to make the processing power transparent to the end-user by using a front-end application server.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The data lake allows an organization to shift its focus from centralized control to a shared model to respond to the changing dynamics of information management.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This enables quick segregation of data into the data lake, thereby reducing the overhead time.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Multidimensional big data can also be represented as OLAP data cubes or, mathematically, tensors.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Array database systems have set out to provide storage and high-level query support on this data type.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Although, many approaches and technologies have been developed, it still remains difficult to carry out machine learning with big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Some MPP relational databases have the ability to store and manage petabytes of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Implicit is the ability to load, monitor, back up, and optimize the use of the large data tables in the RDBMS.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] DARPA's Topological Data Analysis program seeks the fundamental structure of massive data sets and in 2008 the technology went public with the launch of a company called "Ayasdi".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The practitioners of big data analytics processes are generally hostile to slower shared storage, preferring direct-attached storage (DAS) in its various forms from solid state drive (SSD) to high capacity SATA disk buried inside parallel processing nodes.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The perception of shared storage architectures—storage area network (SAN) and network-attached storage (NAS)— is that they are relatively slow, complex, and expensive.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] These qualities are not consistent with big data analytics systems that thrive on system performance, commodity infrastructure, and low cost.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Real or near-real-time information delivery is one of the defining characteristics of big data analytics.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Latency is therefore avoided whenever and wherever possible.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Data in direct-attached memory or disk is good—data on memory or disk at the other end of an FC SAN connection is not.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The cost of an SAN at the scale needed for analytics applications is much higher than other storage techniques.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data has increased the demand of information management specialists so much so that Software AG, Oracle Corporation, IBM, Microsoft, SAP, EMC, HP, and Dell have spent more than $15 billion on software firms specializing in data management and analytics.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In 2010, this industry was worth more than $100 billion and was growing at almost 10 percent a year, about twice as fast as the software business as a whole.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Developed economies increasingly use data-intensive technologies.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] There are 4.6 billion mobile-phone subscriptions worldwide, and between 1 billion and 2 billion people accessing the internet.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Between 1990 and 2005, more than 1 billion people worldwide entered the middle class, which means more people became more literate, which in turn led to information growth.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The world's effective capacity to exchange information through telecommunication networks was 281 petabytes in 1986, 471 petabytes in 1993, 2.2 exabytes in 2000, 65 exabytes in 2007 and predictions put the amount of internet traffic at 667 exabytes annually by 2014.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] According to one estimate, one-third of the globally stored information is in the form of alphanumeric text and still image data, which is the format most useful for most big data applications.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This also shows the potential of yet unused data (i.e. in the form of video and audio content).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] While many vendors offer off-the-shelf products for big data, experts promote the development of in-house custom-tailored systems if the company has sufficient technical capabilities.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The use and adoption of big data within governmental processes allows efficiencies in terms of cost, productivity, and innovation, but comes with flaws.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Data analysis often requires multiple parts of government (central and local) to work in collaboration and create new and innovative processes to deliver the desired outcome.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] A common government organization that makes use of big data is the National Security Agency (NSA), which monitors the activities of the Internet constantly in search for potential patterns of suspicious or illegal activities their system may pick up.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Civil registration and vital statistics (CRVS) collects all certificates status from birth to death.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] CRVS is a source of big data for governments.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Research on the effective usage of information and communication technologies for development (also known as "ICT4D") suggests that big data technology can make important contributions but also present unique challenges to international development.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Advancements in big data analysis offer cost-effective opportunities to improve decision-making in critical development areas such as health care, employment, economic productivity, crime, security, and natural disaster and resource management.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Additionally, user-generated data offers new opportunities to give the unheard a voice.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] However, longstanding challenges for developing regions such as inadequate technological infrastructure and economic and human resource scarcity exacerbate existing concerns with big data such as privacy, imperfect methodology, and interoperability issues.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The challenge of "big data for development" is currently evolving toward the application of this data through machine learning, known as "artificial intelligence for development (AI4D).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] A major practical application of big data for development has been "fighting poverty with data".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In 2015, Blumenstock and colleagues estimated predicted poverty and wealth from mobile phone metadata and in 2016 Jean and colleagues combined satellite imagery and machine learning to predict poverty.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] At the same time, working with digital trace data instead of traditional survey data does not eliminate the traditional challenges involved in the field of international quantitative analysis.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Priorities may change, but the fundamental discussions remain the same.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big Data is being rapidly adopted in Finance to 1) speed up processing and 2) deliver better, more informed inferences, both internally and to the clients of the financial institutions.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big Data has also been a typical concept within the field of alternative financial service.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Some of the major areas involve crowd-funding platforms and crypto currency exchanges.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Some areas of improvement are more aspirational than actually implemented.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The level of data generated within healthcare systems is not trivial.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] With the added adoption of mHealth, eHealth and wearable technologies the volume of data will continue to increase.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This includes electronic health record data, imaging data, patient generated data, sensor data, and other forms of difficult to process data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] There is now an even greater need for such environments to pay greater attention to data and information quality.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] While extensive information in healthcare is now electronic, it fits under the big data umbrella as most is unstructured and difficult to use.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The use of big data in healthcare has raised significant ethical challenges ranging from risks for individual rights, privacy and autonomy, to transparency and trust.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data in health research is particularly promising in terms of exploratory biomedical research, as data-driven analysis can move forward more quickly than hypothesis-driven research.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Then, trends seen in data analysis can be tested in traditional, hypothesis-driven follow up biological research and eventually clinical research.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] A related application sub-area, that heavily relies on big data, within the healthcare field is that of computer-aided diagnosis in medicine.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] For instance, for epilepsy monitoring it is customary to create 5 to 10 GB of data daily.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Similarly, a single uncompressed image of breast tomosynthesis averages 450 MB of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] These are just a few of the many examples where computer-aided diagnosis uses big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] For this reason, big data has been recognized as one of the seven key challenges that computer-aided diagnosis systems need to overcome in order to reach the next level of performance.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] A McKinsey Global Institute study found a shortage of 1.5 million highly trained data professionals and managers and a number of universities including University of Tennessee and UC Berkeley, have created masters programs to meet this demand.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Private boot camps have also developed programs to meet that demand, including paid programs like The Data Incubator or General Assembly.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In the specific field of marketing, one of the problems stressed by Wedel and Kannan is that marketing has several sub domains (e.g., advertising, promotions, product development, branding) that all use different types of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] To understand how the media uses big data, it is first necessary to provide some context into the mechanism used for media process.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] It has been suggested by Nick Couldry and Joseph Turow that practitioners in media and advertising approach big data as many actionable points of information about millions of individuals.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The industry appears to be moving away from the traditional approach of using specific media environments such as newspapers, magazines, or television shows and instead taps into consumers with technologies that reach targeted people at optimal times in optimal locations.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The ultimate aim is to serve or convey, a message or content that is (statistically speaking) in line with the consumer's mindset.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] For example, publishing environments are increasingly tailoring messages (advertisements) and content (articles) to appeal to consumers that have been exclusively gleaned through various data-mining activities.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Channel 4, the British public-service television broadcaster, is a leader in the field of big data and data analysis.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Health insurance providers are collecting data on social "determinants of health" such as food and TV consumption, marital status, clothing size, and purchasing habits, from which they make predictions on health costs, in order to spot health issues in their clients.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] It is controversial whether these predictions are currently being used for pricing.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data and the IoT work in conjunction.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Data extracted from IoT devices provides a mapping of device inter-connectivity.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Such mappings have been used by the media industry, companies, and governments to more accurately target their audience and increase media efficiency.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The IoT is also increasingly adopted as a means of gathering sensory data, and this sensory data has been used in medical, manufacturing and transportation contexts.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Especially since 2015, big data has come to prominence within business operations as a tool to help employees work more efficiently and streamline the collection and distribution of information technology (IT).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The use of big data to resolve IT and data collection issues within an enterprise is called IT operations analytics (ITOA).
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] By applying big data principles into the concepts of machine intelligence and deep computing, IT departments can predict potential issues and prevent them.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] ITOA businesses offer platforms for systems management that bring data silos together and generate insights from the whole of the system rather than from isolated pockets of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Compared to survey-based data collection, big data has low cost per data point, applies analysis techniques via machine learning and data mining, and includes diverse and new data sources, e.g., registers, social media, apps, and other forms digital data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Since 2018, survey scientists have started to examine how big data and survey science can complement each other to allow researchers and practitioners to improve the production of statistics and its quality.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In 2021, the founding members of BigSurv received the Warren J.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Mitofsky Innovators Award from the American Association for Public Opinion Research.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data is notable in marketing due to the constant "datafication" of everyday consumers of the internet, in which all forms of data are tracked.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The datafication of consumers can be defined as quantifying many of or all human behaviors for the purpose of marketing.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The increasingly digital world of rapid datafication makes this idea relevant to marketing because the amount of data constantly grows exponentially.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] It is predicted to increase from 44 to 163 zettabytes within the span of five years.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The size of big data can often be difficult to navigate for marketers.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] As a result, adopters of big data may find themselves at a disadvantage.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Algorithmic findings can be difficult to achieve with such large datasets.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data in marketing is a highly lucrative tool that can be used for large corporations, its value being as a result of the possibility of predicting significant trends, interests, or statistical outcomes in a consumer-based manner.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Real-time market responsiveness is important for marketers because of the ability to shift marketing efforts and correct to current trends, which is helpful in maintaining relevance to consumers.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] This can supply corporations with the information necessary to predict the wants and needs of consumers in advance.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Data-driven market ambidexterity are being highly fueled by big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] New models and algorithms are being developed to make significant predictions about certain economic and social situations.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data can be used to improve training and understanding competitors, using sport sensors.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] It is also possible to predict winners in a match using big data analytics.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Future performance of players could be predicted as well.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Thus, players' value and salary is determined by data collected throughout the season.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In Formula One races, race cars with hundreds of sensors generate terabytes of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] These sensors collect data points from tire pressure to fuel burn efficiency.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Based on the data, engineers and data analysts decide whether adjustments should be made in order to win a race.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Besides, using big data, race teams try to predict the time they will finish the race beforehand, based on simulations using data collected over the season.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, big data was raised as a way to minimise the impact of the disease.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Significant applications of big data included minimizing the spread of the virus, case identification and development of medical treatment.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Governments used big data to track infected people to minimise spread.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Early adopters included China, Taiwan, South Korea, and Israel.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Encrypted search and cluster formation in big data were demonstrated in March 2014 at the American Society of Engineering Education.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Gautam Siwach engaged at *Tackling the challenges of Big Data* by MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory and Amir Esmailpour at the UNH Research Group investigated the key features of big data as the formation of clusters and their interconnections.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] They focused on the security of big data and the orientation of the term towards the presence of different types of data in an encrypted form at cloud interface by providing the raw definitions and real-time examples within the technology.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Moreover, they proposed an approach for identifying the encoding technique to advance towards an expedited search over encrypted text leading to the security enhancements in big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In March 2012, The White House announced a national "Big Data Initiative" that consisted of six federal departments and agencies committing more than $200 million to big data research projects.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The initiative included a National Science Foundation "Expeditions in Computing" grant of $10 million over five years to the AMPLab at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The AMPLab also received funds from DARPA, and over a dozen industrial sponsors and uses big data to attack a wide range of problems from predicting traffic congestion to fighting cancer.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The White House Big Data Initiative also included a commitment by the Department of Energy to provide $25 million in funding over five years to establish the Scalable Data Management, Analysis and Visualization (SDAV) Institute, led by the Energy Department's Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The SDAV Institute aims to bring together the expertise of six national laboratories and seven universities to develop new tools to help scientists manage and visualize data on the department's supercomputers.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The U.S. state of Massachusetts announced the Massachusetts Big Data Initiative in May 2012, which provides funding from the state government and private companies to a variety of research institutions.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology hosts the Intel Science and Technology Center for Big Data in the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, combining government, corporate, and institutional funding and research efforts.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The European Commission is funding the two-year-long Big Data Public Private Forum through their Seventh Framework Program to engage companies, academics and other stakeholders in discussing big data issues.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The project aims to define a strategy in terms of research and innovation to guide supporting actions from the European Commission in the successful implementation of the big data economy.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Outcomes of this project will be used as input for Horizon 2020, their next framework program.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The British government announced in March 2014 the founding of the Alan Turing Institute, named after the computer pioneer and code-breaker, which will focus on new ways to collect and analyze large data sets.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] At the University of Waterloo Stratford Campus Canadian Open Data Experience (CODE) Inspiration Day, participants demonstrated how using data visualization can increase the understanding and appeal of big data sets and communicate their story to the world.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Computational social sciences – Anyone can use application programming interfaces (APIs) provided by big data holders, such as Google and Twitter, to do research in the social and behavioral sciences.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis et al. used Google Trends data to demonstrate that Internet users from countries with a higher per capita gross domestic products (GDPs) are more likely to search for information about the future than information about the past.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The findings suggest there may be a link between online behaviors and real-world economic indicators.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The authors of the study examined Google queries logs made by ratio of the volume of searches for the coming year (2011) to the volume of searches for the previous year (2009), which they call the "future orientation index".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] They compared the future orientation index to the per capita GDP of each country, and found a strong tendency for countries where Google users inquire more about the future to have a higher GDP.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis and his colleagues Helen Susannah Moat and H.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Eugene Stanley introduced a method to identify online precursors for stock market moves, using trading strategies based on search volume data provided by Google Trends.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Their analysis of Google search volume for 98 terms of varying financial relevance, published in *Scientific Reports*, suggests that increases in search volume for financially relevant search terms tend to precede large losses in financial markets.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data sets come with algorithmic challenges that previously did not exist.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Hence, there is seen by some to be a need to fundamentally change the processing ways.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] A research question that is asked about big data sets is whether it is necessary to look at the full data to draw certain conclusions about the properties of the data or if is a sample is good enough.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] The name big data itself contains a term related to size and this is an important characteristic of big data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] But sampling enables the selection of right data points from within the larger data set to estimate the characteristics of the whole population.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] In manufacturing different types of sensory data such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage, and controller data are available at short time intervals.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] To predict downtime it may not be necessary to look at all the data but a sample may be sufficient.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] Big data can be broken down by various data point categories such as demographic, psychographic, behavioral, and transactional data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p01] With large sets of data points, marketers are able to create and use more customized segments of consumers for more strategic targeting.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Critiques of the big data paradigm come in two flavors: those that question the implications of the approach itself, and those that question the way it is currently done.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] One approach to this criticism is the field of critical data studies.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Mark Graham has leveled broad critiques at Chris Anderson's assertion that big data will spell the end of theory: focusing in particular on the notion that big data must always be contextualized in their social, economic, and political contexts.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Even as companies invest eight- and nine-figure sums to derive insight from information streaming in from suppliers and customers, less than 40% of employees have sufficiently mature processes and skills to do so.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] To overcome this insight deficit, big data, no matter how comprehensive or well analyzed, must be complemented by "big judgment", according to an article in the *Harvard Business Review*.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Much in the same line, it has been pointed out that the decisions based on the analysis of big data are inevitably "informed by the world as it was in the past, or, at best, as it currently is".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Fed by a large number of data on past experiences, algorithms can predict future development if the future is similar to the past.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] If the system's dynamics of the future change (if it is not a stationary process), the past can say little about the future.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In order to make predictions in changing environments, it would be necessary to have a thorough understanding of the systems dynamic, which requires theory.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] As a response to this critique Alemany Oliver and Vayre suggest to use "abductive reasoning as a first step in the research process in order to bring context to consumers' digital traces and make new theories emerge".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Additionally, it has been suggested to combine big data approaches with computer simulations, such as agent-based models and complex systems.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Agent-based models are increasingly getting better in predicting the outcome of social complexities of even unknown future scenarios through computer simulations that are based on a collection of mutually interdependent algorithms.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Finally, the use of multivariate methods that probe for the latent structure of the data, such as factor analysis and cluster analysis, have proven useful as analytic approaches that go well beyond the bi-variate approaches (e.g. contingency tables) typically employed with smaller data sets.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In health and biology, conventional scientific approaches are based on experimentation.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] For these approaches, the limiting factor is the relevant data that can confirm or refute the initial hypothesis.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] A new postulate is accepted now in biosciences: the information provided by the data in huge volumes (omics) without prior hypothesis is complementary and sometimes necessary to conventional approaches based on experimentation.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In the massive approaches it is the formulation of a relevant hypothesis to explain the data that is the limiting factor.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] The search logic is reversed and the limits of induction ("Glory of Science and Philosophy scandal", C.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Privacy advocates are concerned about the threat to privacy represented by increasing storage and integration of personally identifiable information; expert panels have released various policy recommendations to conform practice to expectations of privacy.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] The misuse of big data in several cases by media, companies, and even the government has allowed for abolition of trust in almost every fundamental institution holding up society.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Barocas and Nissenbaum argue that one way of protecting individual users is by being informed about the types of information being collected, with whom it is shared, under what constraints and for what purposes.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] The "V" model of big data is concerning as it centers around computational scalability and lacks in a loss around the perceptibility and understandability of information.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Large data sets have been analyzed by computing machines for well over a century, including the US census analytics performed by IBM's punch-card machines which computed statistics including means and variances of populations across the whole continent.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In more recent decades, science experiments such as CERN have produced data on similar scales to current commercial "big data".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Ulf-Dietrich Reips and Uwe Matzat wrote in 2014 that big data had become a "fad" in scientific research.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Researcher danah boyd has raised concerns about the use of big data in science neglecting principles such as choosing a representative sample by being too concerned about handling the huge amounts of data.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] This approach may lead to results that have a bias in one way or another.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Integration across heterogeneous data resources—some that might be considered big data and others not—presents formidable logistical as well as analytical challenges, but many researchers argue that such integrations are likely to represent the most promising new frontiers in science.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In the provocative article "Critical Questions for Big Data", the authors title big data a part of mythology: "large data sets offer a higher form of intelligence and knowledge [...], with the aura of truth, objectivity, and accuracy".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Users of big data are often "lost in the sheer volume of numbers", and "working with Big Data is still subjective, and what it quantifies does not necessarily have a closer claim on objective truth".
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Recent developments in BI domain, such as pro-active reporting especially target improvements in the usability of big data, through automated filtering of non-useful data and correlations.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Big data analysis is often shallow compared to analysis of smaller data sets.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In many big data projects, there is no large data analysis happening, but the challenge is the extract, transform, load part of data pre-processing.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Big data is a buzzword and a "vague term", but at the same time an "obsession" with entrepreneurs, consultants, scientists, and the media.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Big data showcases such as Google Flu Trends failed to deliver good predictions in recent years, overstating the flu outbreaks by a factor of two.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Similarly, Academy Awards and election predictions solely based on Twitter were more often off than on target.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Big data often poses the same challenges as small data; adding more data does not solve problems of bias, but may emphasize other problems.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In particular data sources such as Twitter are not representative of the overall population, and results drawn from such sources may then lead to wrong conclusions.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Google Translate—which is based on big data statistical analysis of text—does a good job at translating web pages.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] However, results from specialized domains may be dramatically skewed.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] On the other hand, big data may also introduce new problems, such as the multiple comparisons problem: simultaneously testing a large set of hypotheses is likely to produce many false results that mistakenly appear significant.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Furthermore, big data analytics results are only as good as the model on which they are predicated.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] In an example, big data took part in attempting to predict the results of the 2016 U.S. presidential election with varying degrees of success.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Big data has been used in policing and surveillance by institutions like law enforcement and corporations ().
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Due to the less visible nature of data-based surveillance as compared to traditional methods of policing, objections to big data policing are less likely to arise.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] If these potential problems are not corrected or regulated, the effects of big data policing may continue to shape societal hierarchies.
[src:industry-4-0/big-data-p02] Brayne also notes that the conscientious use of big data policing could prevent individual-level biases from becoming institutional biases.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] CPS involves transdisciplinary approaches, merging theory of cybernetics, mechatronics, design and process science.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] The process control is often referred to as embedded systems.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] In embedded systems, the emphasis tends to be more on the computational elements, and less on an intense link between the computational and physical elements.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] CPS is also similar to the Internet of Things (IoT), sharing the same basic architecture; nevertheless, CPS presents a higher combination and coordination between physical and computational elements.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Examples of CPS include smart grid, autonomous automobile systems, medical monitoring, industrial control systems, robotics systems, recycling and automatic pilot avionics.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Precursors of cyber-physical systems can be found in areas as diverse as aerospace, automotive, chemical processes, civil infrastructure, energy, healthcare, manufacturing, transportation, entertainment, and consumer appliances.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Unlike more traditional embedded systems, a full-fledged CPS is typically designed as a network of interacting elements with physical input and output instead of as standalone devices.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] The notion is closely tied to concepts of robotics and sensor networks with intelligence mechanisms proper of computational intelligence leading the pathway.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Ongoing advances in science and engineering improve the link between computational and physical elements by means of intelligent mechanisms, increasing the adaptability, autonomy, efficiency, functionality, reliability, safety, and usability of cyber-physical systems.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Mobile cyber-physical systems, in which the physical system under study has inherent mobility, are a prominent subcategory of cyber-physical systems.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Examples of mobile physical systems include mobile robotics and electronics transported by humans or animals.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] The rise in popularity of smartphones has increased interest in the area of mobile cyber-physical systems.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Examples of mobile cyber-physical systems include applications to track and analyze CO2 emissions, detect traffic accidents, insurance telematics and provide situational awareness services to first responders, measure traffic, and monitor cardiac patients.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Common applications of CPS typically fall under sensor-based communication-enabled autonomous systems.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] For example, many wireless sensor networks monitor some aspect of the environment and relay the processed information to a central node.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Other types of CPS include smart grid, autonomous automotive systems, medical monitoring, process control systems, distributed robotics, recycling and automatic pilot avionics.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] A real-world example of such a system is the Distributed Robot Garden at MIT in which a team of robots tend a garden of tomato plants.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] This system combines distributed sensing (each plant is equipped with a sensor node monitoring its status), navigation, manipulation and wireless networking.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] A focus on the control system aspects of CPS that pervade critical infrastructure can be found in the efforts of the Idaho National Laboratory and collaborators researching resilient control systems.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] This effort takes a holistic approach to next generation design, and considers the resilience aspects that are not well quantified, such as cyber security, human interaction and complex interdependencies.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Another example is MIT's ongoing CarTel project where a fleet of taxis work by collecting real-time traffic information in the Boston area.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Together with historical data, this information is then used for calculating fastest routes for a given time of the day.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] CPS are also used in electric grids to perform advanced control, especially in the smart grids context to enhance the integration of distributed renewable generation.The Special remedial action scheme are needed to limit the current flows in the grid when wind farm generation is too high.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] In industry the cyber-physical systems empowered by Cloud technologies have led to novel approaches that paved the path to Industry 4.0 as the European Commission IMC-AESOP project with partners such as Schneider Electric, SAP, Honeywell, Microsoft etc. demonstrated.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] In the area of digital agriculture (alternately precision agriculture), CPS technologies are used for measurement of soil quality and moisture content and determining the right level of irrigation or fertilizer or pesticide usage.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] A challenge in the development of embedded and cyber-physical systems is the large differences in the design practice between the various engineering disciplines involved, such as software and mechanical engineering.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Additionally, as of today there is no "language" in terms of design practice that is common to all the involved disciplines in CPS.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Today, in a marketplace where rapid innovation is assumed to be essential, engineers from all disciplines need to be able to explore system designs collaboratively, allocating responsibilities to software and physical elements, and analyzing trade-offs between them.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Recent advances show that coupling disciplines by using co-simulation will allow disciplines to cooperate without enforcing new tools or design methods.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Results from the MODELISAR project show that this approach is viable by proposing a new standard for co-simulation in the form of the Functional Mock-up Interface.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] The US National Science Foundation (NSF) has identified cyber-physical systems as a key area of research.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Through its CPS Program, it awards "Frontier" projects that are large-scale projects ($5-7M each) meant to significantly move the CPS technology forward.
[src:industry-4-0/cyber-physical-system] Starting in late 2006, the NSF and other United States federal agencies sponsored several workshops on cyber-physical systems.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] The goal for its implementation is to increase value through innovation, invention, improved customer experience and efficiency.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] However, since there are no comprehensive data sets on digital transformation at the macro level, the overall effect of digital transformation is still (as of 2020), too early to comment.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] This approach focuses on step-by-step transformation instead of the all-or-nothing approach.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] A few benefits of DDP are risk mitigation, quick response to changing market conditions, and increased success rate to digital transformations.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Adopting digital technology can bring various benefits to a business.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] CIPS has also observed that digital capability can be used to support supply chain transparency and remote working.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] There are multiple common barriers that digital transformation initiatives, projects and strategies face.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] One of the main barriers is change management, because changes in processes may face active resistance from workers.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Related to change management is the miscommunication between workers, which can lead to implementation delays or even complete project failure.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Some companies are unable to develop a realistic cost projection due to a too optimistic view of the process.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Companies may have legacy systems in place, which can lead to integration difficulties with new systems.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Within organizations there may also be a lack of resources, top management support, workers' skills, commitment, collaboration and vision.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Some company cultures can struggle with the changes required by digital transformation.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] In addition to the several barriers to digital transformation, there are also numerous enablers of digital transformation.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] The primary enablers are organizations' resources and capabilities, workers' skills, technologies and culture.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] The aforementioned enabler "Organizations resources and capabilities" refers to the ability of an organization to adapt to contemporary issues arising in the business environment, as well as their capabilities in the field of data analytics.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Regarding "Workers' skills", workers must be able to develop valuable insights with the use of data, have significant emotional intelligence and effectively partake in the development of new products.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Thirdly, technology is also a vital enabler of digital transformation.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Companies can benefit from having access to artificial intelligence, data analytics software and effective usage of social media.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Lastly, "Culture" pertains to the extent the organizational culture is data-driven and the quality of the top management support and engagement within the corporation.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Digitization is the process of converting analog information into digital form using an analog-to-digital converter, such as in an image scanner or for digital audio recordings.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] As usage of the internet has increased since the 1990s, the usage of digitization has also increased.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Digital transformation, however, is broader than just the digitization of existing processes.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Digital transformation entails considering how products, processes and organizations can be changed through the use of new digital technologies.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] A 2019 review proposes a definition of digital transformation as "a process that aims to improve an entity by triggering significant changes to its properties through combinations of information, computing, communication, and connectivity technologies".
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Digital transformation can be seen as a socio-technical programme.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] A 2015 report stated that maturing digital companies were using cloud hosting, social media, mobile devices and data analytics, while other companies were using individual technologies for specific problems.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] By 2017, one study found that less than 40% of industries had become digitized (although usage was high in the media, retail and technology industries).
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] As of 2020, 37% of European companies and 27% of American companies had not embraced digital technology.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Over the period of 2017 to 2020, 70% of European municipalities have increased their spending on digital technologies.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] In a 2021 survey, 55% of European companies stated the COVID-19 pandemic has increased the demand for digital technology, and 46% of companies reported that they have grown more digital.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Half of these companies anticipate an increase in the usage of digital technologies in the future, with a greater proportion being companies that have previously used digital technology.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] A lack of digital infrastructure was viewed as a key barrier to investment by 16% of EU businesses, compared to 5% in the US.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] In a survey conducted in 2021, 89% of African banks polled claimed that the pandemic had hastened the digital transformation of their internal operations.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] In 2022, 53% of businesses in the EU reported taking action or making investments in becoming more digital.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] 71% of companies in the US reported using at least one advanced digital technology, similar to the average usage of 69% across EU organizations.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Digital transformation plays a crucial role in alleviating the adverse effects of simultaneous and interconnected challenges, while also strengthening the resilience and adaptability of both organizations and supply chains.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Represented by the TOP framework, digital transformation acts as a catalyst for generating and leveraging benefits.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] These benefits hold the potential to bolster resilience across not only individual organizations but also throughout the entire supply chain.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] It does so by leveraging cutting-edge technologies to enhance predictive power and responsiveness.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Technologies include the Internet of Things, big data analytics, artificial intelligence, simulation, additive manufacturing, blockchain, and digital twins.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Digital transformation within organizational culture is associated with changes in management practices, collaboration across departments, and supply chains.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] It also relates to organizational responses to operational changes.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Organizational communication involves coordination between departments and employees.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Management skills in communication, leadership, and strategy are applied in organizational operations and in addressing challenges.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] According to the resource-based view theory, successful firms' resources should be valuable, rare, non-imitable, and non-substitutable in order for capabilities such as responsiveness, flexibility, or even agility to be developed.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] "A capability is a concept that refers to an organization's use of a set of resources to carry out its routine and strategic activities".
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] The digital transformation capability (DTC) framework is a direct application of this theory, stating that resources can be either tangible, intangible or human.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] The tangible side of the DTC framework gathers physical assets like the organization's IT infrastructure, whereas the intangible side focuses on its digital transformation strategy, knowledge, and reputational capital.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Human resources are broader and include technical skills, continuous training, leadership, and social skills.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Digital transformation is often described as a reactive response to factors such as customer demands, competitive pressures, and regulatory requirements.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] However, it can be a proactive opportunity for organizations to achieve sustainable business practices and facilitate a circular economy.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] By building sensing, smart, sustainable, and social capabilities, enterprises can capture valuable information, make faster and smarter decisions, and adapt to changing environments.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] Aligning digital transformation with sustainability can enhance performance by engaging stakeholders, optimizing resource allocation, and reducing risks.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] A comprehensive business case that prioritizes sustainability benefits and multidimensional returns can secure the necessary resources for successful implementation.
[src:industry-4-0/digital-transformation] To achieve sustainability goals, effective governance, integration, change management, and stakeholder involvement are critical factors.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The **industrial Internet of things** (**IIoT**) refers to interconnected sensors, instruments, and other devices networked together with computers' industrial applications, including manufacturing and energy management.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] This connectivity allows for data collection, exchange, and analysis, potentially facilitating improvements in productivity and efficiency as well as other economic benefits.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is an evolution of a distributed control system (DCS) that allows for a higher degree of automation by using cloud computing to refine and optimize the process controls.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is enabled by technologies such as cybersecurity, cloud computing, edge computing, mobile technologies, machine-to-machine, 3D printing, advanced robotics, big data, Internet of things, RFID technology, and cognitive computing.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT systems are usually conceived as a layered modular architecture of digital technology.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The device layer refers to the physical components: CPS, sensors or machines.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The network layer consists of physical network buses, cloud computing and communication protocols that aggregate and transport the data to the service layer, which consists of applications that manipulate and combine data into information that can be displayed on the driver dashboard.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The top-most stratum of the stack is the content layer or the user interface.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The history of the IIoT begins with the invention of the programmable logic controller (PLC) by Richard E.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Morley in 1968, which was used by General Motors in their automatic transmission manufacturing division.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] These PLCs allowed for fine control of individual elements in the manufacturing chain.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] In 1975, Honeywell and Yokogawa introduced the world's first DCSs, the TDC 2000 and the CENTUM system, respectively.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] These DCSs were the next step in allowing flexible process control throughout a plant, with the added benefit of backup redundancies by distributing control across the entire system, eliminating a singular point of failure in a central control room.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] As early as in 1994, greater industrial applications were envisioned, as Reza Raji described the concept in IEEE Spectrum as "[moving] small packets of data to a large set of nodes, so as to integrate and automate everything from home appliances to entire factories".
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The concept of the Internet of things first became popular in 1999, through the Auto-ID Center at MIT and related market-analysis publications.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Radio-frequency identification (RFID) was seen by Kevin Ashton (one of the founders of the original Auto-ID Center) as a prerequisite for the Internet of things at that point.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] If all objects and people in daily life were equipped with identifiers, computers could manage and inventory them.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Besides using RFID, the tagging of things may be achieved through such technologies as near field communication, barcodes, QR codes and digital watermarking.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the first consequences of implementing the industrial internet of things (by equipping objects with minuscule identifying devices or machine-readable identifiers) would be to create instant and ceaseless inventory control.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Another benefit of implementing an IIoT system is the ability to create a digital twin of the system.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Using this digital twin allows for further optimization of the system by allowing for experimentation with new data from the cloud without having to halt production or sacrifice safety, as the new processes can be refined virtually until they are ready to be implemented.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] A digital twin can also serve as a training ground for new employees who won't have to worry about real impacts on the live system.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] IoT frameworks help support the interaction between "things" and allow for more complex structures like distributed computing and the development of distributed applications.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The term industrial internet of things is often encountered in the manufacturing industries, referring to the industrial subset of the IoT.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Potential benefits of the industrial internet of things include improved productivity, improved reliability, analytics and the transformation of the workplace.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The potential of growth by implementing IIoT is predicted to generate $15 trillion of global GDP by 2030.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] While connectivity and data acquisition are imperative for IIoT, they are not the end goals, but rather the foundation and path to something bigger.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Of all the technologies, predictive maintenance is an "easier” application, as it is applicable to existing assets and management systems.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Intelligent maintenance systems can reduce unexpected downtime and increase productivity, which is projected to save up to 12% over scheduled repairs, reduce overall maintenance costs up to 30%, and eliminate breakdowns up to 70%, according to some studies.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Cyber-physical systems (CPS) are the core technology of industrial big data and they will be an interface between human and the cyber world.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Integration of sensing and actuation systems connected to the Internet can optimize energy consumption as a whole.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] It is expected that IoT devices will be integrated into all forms of energy consuming devices (switches, power outlets, bulbs, televisions, etc.) and be able to communicate with the utility supply company in order to effectively balance power generation and energy usage.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) devices connected to the Internet backbone, electric utilities can not only collect data from end-user connections, but also manage other distribution automation devices like transformers and reclosers.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Using IIoT in car manufacturing implies the digitalization of all elements of production.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Software, machines, and humans are interconnected, enabling suppliers and manufacturers to rapidly respond to changing standards.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT enables efficient and cost-effective production by moving data from the customers to the company's systems, and then to individual sections of the production process.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIoT, new tools and functionalities can be included in the manufacturing process.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] For example, 3D printers simplify the way of shaping pressing tools by printing the shape directly from steel granulate.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] These tools enable new possibilities for designing (with high precision).
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Customization of vehicles is also enabled by IIoT due to the modularity and connectivity of this technology.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] While in the past they worked separately, IIoT now enables humans and robots to cooperate.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Robots take on heavy and repetitive activities, so the manufacturing cycles are quicker and the vehicle comes to the market more rapidly.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Factories can quickly identify potential maintenance issues before they lead to downtime and many of them are moving to a 24-hour production plant, due to higher security and efficiency.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The majority of automotive manufacturers companies have production plants in different countries, where different components of the same vehicle are built.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT makes it possible to connect these production plants to each other, creating the possibility to move within facilities.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Big data can be visually monitored which enables companies to respond faster to fluctuations in production and demand.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT support, large amounts of raw data can be stored and sent by the drilling gear and research stations for cloud storage and analysis.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT technologies, the oil and gas industry has the capability to connect machines, devices, sensors, and people through interconnectivity, which can help companies better address fluctuations in demand and pricing, address cybersecurity, and minimize environmental impact.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Across the supply chain, IIOT can improve the maintenance process, the overall safety, and connectivity.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Drones can be used to detect possible oil and gas leaks at an early stage and at locations that are difficult to reach (e.g. offshore).
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] They can also be used to identify weak spots in complex networks of pipelines with built-in thermal imaging systems.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Increased connectivity (data integration and communication) can help companies with adjusting the production levels based on real-time data of inventory, storage, distribution pace, and forecasted demand.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows monitoring of pipeline threats, improving risk management, and providing situational awareness.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Benefits also apply to specific processes of the oil and gas industry.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The exploration process of oil and gas can be done more precisely with 4D models built by seismic imaging.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] These models map fluctuations in oil reserves and gas levels, they strive to point out the exact quantity of resources needed, and they forecast the lifespan of wells.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The application of smart sensors and automated drillers gives companies the opportunity to monitor and produce more efficiently.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Further, the storing process can also be improved with the implementation of IIOT by collecting and analyzing real-time data to monitor inventory levels and temperature control.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] IIOT can enhance the transportation process of oil and gas by implementing smart sensors and thermal detectors to give real-time geolocation data and monitor the products for safety reasons.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] These smart sensors can monitor the refinery processes, and enhance safety.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The demand for products can be forecasted more precisely and automatically be communicated to the refineries and production plants to adjust production levels.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] In the agriculture industry, IIoT helps farmers to make decisions about when to harvest.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Sensors collect data about soil and weather conditions and propose schedules for fertilizing and irrigating.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Some livestock farms implant microchips into animals.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows the farmers not only to trace their animals, but also pull up information about the lineage, weight, or health.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The integration of IIoT data in the photovoltaic (PV) industry can significantly enhance the efficiency, reliability, and performance of solar power systems.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT with AI data can be utilized for real-time monitoring, performance optimization, fault detection, diagnostics.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] As the IIoT expands, new security concerns arise with it.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Every new device or component that connects to the IIoT can become a potential liability.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Gartner estimates that by 2020, more than 25% of recognized attacks on enterprises will involve IoT-connected systems, despite accounting for less than 10% of IT security budgets.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Existing cybersecurity measures are vastly inferior for Internet-connected devices compared to their traditional computer counterparts, which can allow for them to be hijacked for DDoS-based attacks by botnets like Mirai.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Another possibility is the infection of Internet-connected industrial controllers, like in the case of Stuxnet, without the need for physical access to the system to spread the worm.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Additionally, IIoT-enabled devices can allow for more “traditional” forms of cybercrime, as in the case of the 2013 Target data breach, where information was stolen after hackers gained access to Target's networks via credentials stolen from a third party HVAC vendor.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] The pharmaceutical manufacturing industry has been slow to adopt IIoT advances because of security concerns such as these.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the difficulties in providing security solutions in IIoT applications is the fragmented nature of the hardware.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Consequently, security architectures are turning towards designs that are software-based or device-agnostic.
[src:industry-4-0/industrial-internet-of-things] Hardware-based approaches, like the use of data diodes, are often used when connecting critical infrastructure.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The **Fourth Industrial Revolution**, also known as **4IR**, **Industry 4.0** or the **Intelligence Age**, is a neologism describing rapid technological advancement in the 21st century.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It follows the Third Industrial Revolution (the "Information Age").
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The term was popularized in 2016 by Klaus Schwab, the World Economic Forum founder and former executive chairman, who asserts that these developments represent a significant shift in industrial capitalism.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] A part of this phase of industrial change is the joining of technologies like artificial intelligence, gene editing, to advanced robotics that blur the lines between the physical, digital, and biological worlds.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] This integration results in increasing automation, improving communication and self-monitoring, and the use of smart machines that can analyse and diagnose issues without the need for human intervention.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It also represents a social, political, and economic shift from the digital age of the late 1990s and early 2000s to an era of embedded connectivity distinguished by the ubiquity of technology in society that changes the ways humans experience and know the world around them.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It posits that we have created and are entering an augmented social reality compared to just the natural senses and industrial ability of humans alone.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Fourth Industrial Revolution is sometimes expected to mark the beginning of an *imagination age*, where creativity and imagination become the primary drivers of economic value.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The phrase *Fourth Industrial Revolution* was first introduced by a team of scientists developing a high-tech strategy for the German government.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Klaus Schwab, former executive chairman of the World Economic Forum (WEF), introduced the phrase to a wider audience in a 2015 article published by *Foreign Affairs*.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] "Mastering the Fourth Industrial Revolution" was the 2016 theme of the World Economic Forum Annual Meeting, in Davos-Klosters, Switzerland.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] On 10 October 2016, the Forum announced the opening of its Centre for the Fourth Industrial Revolution in San Francisco.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] This was also subject and title of Schwab's 2016 book.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Schwab includes in this fourth era technologies that combine hardware, software, and biology (cyber-physical systems), and emphasizes advances in communication and connectivity.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In *The Great Reset* proposal by the WEF, *The Fourth Industrial Revolution* is included as a strategic intelligence in the solution to rebuild the economy sustainably following the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The First Industrial Revolution was marked by a transition from hand production methods to machines through the use of steam power and water power.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The implementation of new technologies took a long time, so the period which this refers to was between 1760 and 1820, or 1840 in Europe and the United States.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Its effects had consequences on textile manufacturing, which was first to adopt such changes, as well as iron industry, agriculture, and mining–although it also had societal effects with an ever stronger middle class.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Second Industrial Revolution, also known as the Technological Revolution, is the period between 1871 and 1914 that resulted from installations of extensive railroad and telegraph networks, which allowed for faster transfer of people and ideas, as well as electricity.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Increasing electrification allowed for factories to develop the modern production line.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Third Industrial Revolution, also known as the Digital Revolution, began in the late 20th century.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It is characterized by the shift to an economy centered on information technology, marked by the advent of personal computers, the Internet, and the widespread digitalization of communication and industrial processes.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] A book by Jeremy Rifkin titled *The Third Industrial Revolution*, published in 2011, focused on the intersection of digital communications technology and renewable energy.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It was made into a 2017 documentary by Vice Media.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In essence, the Fourth Industrial Revolution is the trend towards automation and data exchange in manufacturing technologies and processes which include cyber-physical systems (CPS), internet of things (IoT), cloud computing, cognitive computing, and artificial intelligence.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Machines improve human efficiency in performing repetitive functions, and the combination of machine learning and computing power allows machines to carry out increasingly complex tasks.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It also emphasizes decentralized decisions – the ability of cyber physical systems to make decisions on their own and to perform their tasks as autonomously as possible.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Only in the case of exceptions, interference, or conflicting goals, are tasks delegated to a higher level.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Proponents of the Fourth Industrial Revolution suggest it is a distinct revolution rather than simply a prolongation of the Third Industrial Revolution.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Critics of the concept dismiss Industry 4.0 as a marketing strategy.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] They suggest that although revolutionary changes are identifiable in distinct sectors, there is no systemic change so far.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In addition, the pace of recognition of Industry 4.0 and policy transition varies across countries; the definition of Industry 4.0 is not harmonised.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] One of the most known figures is Jeremy Rifkin who "agree[s] that digitalization is the hallmark and defining technology in what has become known as the Third Industrial Revolution".
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] However, he argues "that the evolution of digitalization has barely begun to run its course and that its new configuration in the form of the Internet of Things represents the next stage of its development".
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 networks a wide range of new technologies to create value.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Using cyber-physical systems that monitor physical processes, a virtual copy of the physical world can be designed.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Characteristics of cyber-physical systems include the ability to make decentralised decisions independently, reaching a high degree of autonomy.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The value created in Industry 4.0 can be relied upon in electronic identification, in which the smart manufacturing requires set technologies to be incorporated in the manufacturing process to thus be classified as in the development path of Industry 4.0 and no longer digitisation.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Fourth Industrial Revolution fosters "smart factories", which are production environments where facilities and logistics systems are organised with minimal human intervention.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The technical foundations on which smart factories are based are cyber-physical systems that communicate with each other using IoT.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] An important part of this process is the exchange of data between the product and the production line.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] This enables more efficient supply chain connectivity and better organisation within a production environment.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Within modular structured smart factories, cyber-physical systems monitor physical processes, create a virtual copy of the physical world, and make decentralised decisions.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Over the internet of things, cyber-physical systems communicate and cooperate with each other and with humans in synchronic time both internally and across organizational services offered and used by participants of the value chain.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Artificial intelligence (AI) has a wide range of applications across all sectors of the economy.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It gained prominence following advancements in deep learning during the 2010s, and its impact intensified in the 2020s with the rise of generative AI, a period often referred to as the "AI boom".
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Models like GPT-4o can engage in verbal and textual discussions and analyse images.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] AI is a key driver of Industry 4.0, orchestrating technologies like robotics, automated vehicles, and real-time data analytics.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] By enabling machines to perform complex tasks, AI is redefining production processes and reducing changeover times.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] AI could also significantly accelerate, or even automate software development.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Some experts believe that AI alone could be as transformative as an industrial revolution.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Multiple companies such as OpenAI and Meta have expressed the goal of creating artificial general intelligence (AI that can do virtually any cognitive task a human can), making large investments in data centres and GPUs to train more capable AI models.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Humanoid robots have traditionally lacked usefulness.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] They had difficulty picking simple objects due to imprecise control and coordination, and they wouldn't understand their environment and how physics works.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] They were often explicitly programmed to do narrow tasks, failing when encountering new situations.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Modern humanoid robots, however, are typically based on machine learning, and in particular reinforcement learning.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In 2024, humanoid robots are rapidly becoming more flexible, easier to train, and versatile.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 facilitates predictive maintenance, due to the use of advanced technologies, including IoT sensors.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Predictive maintenance, which can identify potential maintenance issues in real time, allows machine owners to perform cost-effective maintenance before the machinery fails or gets damaged.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] For example, a company in Los Angeles could understand if a piece of equipment in Singapore is running at an abnormal speed or temperature.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] They could then decide whether or not it needs to be repaired.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Fourth Industrial Revolution is said to have extensive dependency on 3D printing technology.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Some advantages of 3D printing for industry are that 3D printing can print many geometric structures, as well as simplify the product design process.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It is also relatively environmentally friendly.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In low-volume production, it can also decrease lead times and total production costs.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Moreover, it can increase flexibility, reduce warehousing costs and help the company towards the adoption of a mass customisation business strategy.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In addition, 3D printing can be very useful for printing spare parts and installing it locally, therefore reducing supplier dependence and reducing the supply lead time.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Sensors and instrumentation drive the central forces of innovation, not only for Industry 4.0 but also for other "smart" megatrends, such as smart production, smart mobility, smart homes, smart cities, and smart factories.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Smart sensors are devices which generate the data and allow further functionality from self-monitoring and self-configuration to condition monitoring of complex processes.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] With the capability of wireless communication, they reduce installation effort to a great extent and help realise a dense array of sensors.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] However, there are a few issues, such as time synchronisation error, data loss, and dealing with large amounts of harvested data, which all limit the implementation of full-fledged systems.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Moreover, additional limits on these functionalities represent the battery power.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Smart sensors in these two fields are still in the testing stage.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] These connected sensors collect, interpret and communicate the information available in the plots (leaf area, vegetation index, chlorophyll, hygrometry, temperature, water potential, radiation).
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Based on this scientific data, the objective is to enable real-time monitoring via a smartphone with a range of advice that optimises plot management in terms of results, time and costs.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] On the farm, these sensors can be used to detect crop stages and recommend inputs and treatments at the right time, as well as controlling the level of irrigation.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The food industry requires more and more security and transparency and full documentation is required.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] This new technology is used as a tracking system as well as the collection of human data and product data.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Knowledge economy is an economic system in which production and services are largely based on knowledge-intensive activities that contribute to an accelerated pace of technical and scientific advance, as well as rapid obsolescence.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 aids transitions into knowledge economy by increasing reliance on intellectual capabilities rather than on physical inputs or natural resources.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Many countries have set up institutional mechanisms to foster the adoption of Industry 4.0 technologies.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Australia has a Digital Transformation Agency (est.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] 2015) and the Prime Minister's Industry 4.0 Taskforce (est.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] 2016), which promotes collaboration with industry groups in Germany and the USA.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Brazil's embrace of Industry 4.0 technologies has been a slow and inconsistent process.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Initial assessments clearly indicated a considerable gap in digital preparedness among the nation's industrial businesses.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] A significant survey, conducted by the National Confederation of Industry, revealed concerning statistics: 42% of Brazilian companies were completely unaware of how crucial digital technologies are for industrial competitiveness.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Furthermore, a substantial 46% either weren't utilizing these technologies or were unsure about their application.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] These findings collectively underscored a widespread lack of awareness and readiness for digital transformation across the Brazilian industrial landscape.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The term "Industrie 4.0" was publicly introduced in the same year at the Hannover Fair.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] German professor Wolfgang Wahlster is sometimes called the inventor of the "Industry 4.0" term.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In October 2012, the Working Group on Industry 4.0 presented a set of Industry 4.0 implementation recommendations to the German federal government.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The workgroup members and partners are recognised as the founding fathers and driving force behind Industry 4.0.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] On 8 April 2013 at the Hannover Fair, the final report of the Working Group Industry 4.0 was presented.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] This working group was headed by Siegfried Dais, of Robert Bosch GmbH, and Henning Kagermann, of the German Academy of Science and Engineering.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] As Industry 4.0 principles have been applied by companies, they have sometimes been rebranded.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] For example, the aerospace parts manufacturer Meggitt PLC has branded its own Industry 4.0 research project M4.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In Germany, the impact of the shift to Industry 4.0 (and especially digitisation) on the labour market has been discussed under the heading "Work 4.0".
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The federal government in Germany is a leader in the development of the I4.0 policy through its ministries of the German federal Ministry of Education and Research (BMBF) and BMWi.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Through the publishing of set objectives and goals for enterprises to achieve, the German federal government attempts to set the direction of the digital transformation.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] However, there is a gap between German enterprise's collaboration and knowledge of these set policies.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The biggest challenge SMEs in Germany are currently facing regarding digital transformation of their manufacturing processes is ensuring that there is a concrete IT and application landscape to support further digital transformation efforts.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The characteristics of the German government's Industry 4.0 strategy involve the strong customisation of products under the conditions of highly flexible (mass-) production.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The required automation technology is improved by the introduction of methods of self-optimization, self-configuration, self-diagnosis, cognition and intelligent support of workers in their increasingly complex work.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The largest project in Industry 4.0 as of July 2013 is the BMBF leading-edge cluster "Intelligent Technical Systems Ostwestfalen-Lippe (its OWL)".
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Another major project is the BMBF project RES-COM, as well as the Cluster of Excellence "Integrative Production Technology for High-Wage Countries".
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In 2015, the European Commission started the international Horizon 2020 research project CREMA (cloud-based rapid elastic manufacturing) as a major initiative to foster the Industry 4.0 topic.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In Estonia, the digital transformation dubbed as the 4th Industrial Revolution by Klaus Schwab and the World Economic Forum in 2015 started with the restoration of independence in 1991.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Although a latecomer to the information revolution due to 50 years of Soviet occupation, Estonia leapfrogged to the digital era, while skipping the analogue connections almost completely.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The early decisions made by Prime Minister Mart Laar on the course of the country's economic development led to the establishment of what is today known as e-Estonia, one of the worlds most digitally advanced nations.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Another example is the Indonesian initiative Making Indonesia 4.0, which focuses on improving industrial performance.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] India, with its expanding economy and extensive manufacturing sector, has embraced the digital revolution, leading to significant advancements in manufacturing.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Indian program for Industry 4.0 centres around leveraging technology to produce globally competitive products at cost-effective rates while adopting the latest technological advancements of Industry 4.0.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Society 5.0 envisions a society that prioritizes the well-being of its citizens, striking a harmonious balance between economic progress and the effective addressing of societal challenges through a closely interconnected system of both the digital realm and the physical world.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] This concept was introduced in 2019 in the 5th Science and Technology Basic Plan for Japanese Government as a blueprint for a forthcoming societal framework.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Malaysia's national policy on Industry 4.0 is known as Industry4WRD.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Launched in 2018, key initiatives in this policy include enhancing digital infrastructure, equipping the workforce with 4IR skills, and fostering innovation and technology adoption across industries.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] South Africa appointed a Presidential Commission on the Fourth Industrial Revolution in 2019, consisting of about 30 stakeholders with a background in academia, industry and government.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] South Africa has also established an Inter ministerial Committee on Industry 4.0.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] A nationwide survey of 577 lecturers in Technical Engineering at 52 TVET college campuses across South Africa found that 52.3% of participants were unaware of technological advancements in their area of specialization and their potential impact on technical training.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] These findings indicate that South African TVET lecturers have limited awareness of the technological advancements needed to participate effectively in the 4IR era.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Accordingly, South African Minister of Higher Education, Blade Nzimande, placed the upskilling of TVET lecturers' 4IR-related skills high on the ministry's agenda.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Republic of Korea has had a Presidential Committee on the Fourth Industrial Revolution since 2017.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Republic of Korea's I-Korea strategy (2017) is focusing on new growth engines that include AI, drones, and autonomous cars, in line with the government's innovation-driven economic policy.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In a policy paper published in 2019, the UK's Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy, titled "Regulation for the Fourth Industrial Revolution", outlined the need to evolve current regulatory models to remain competitive in evolving technological and social settings.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The Department of Homeland Security in 2019 published a paper called 'The Industrial Internet of things (IIOT): Opportunities, Risks, Mitigation'.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The base pieces of critical infrastructure are increasingly digitised for greater connectivity and optimisation.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Hence, its implementation, growth and maintenance must be carefully planned and safeguarded.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The paper discusses not only applications of IIOT but also the associated risks.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] It has suggested some key areas where risk mitigation is possible.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] To increase coordination between the public, private, law enforcement, academia and other stakeholders the DHS formed the National Cybersecurity and Communications Integration Center (NCCIC).
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The aerospace industry has sometimes been characterised as "too low volume for extensive automation".
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] However, Industry 4.0 principles have been investigated by several aerospace companies, and technologies have been developed to improve productivity where the upfront cost of automation cannot be justified.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] One example of this is the aerospace parts manufacturer Meggitt PLC's M4 project.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] The increasing use of the industrial internet of things is referred to as Industry 4.0 at Bosch, and generally in Germany.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 inspired Innovation 4.0, a move toward digitisation for academia and research and development.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] In 2017, the £81M Materials Innovation Factory (MIF) at the University of Liverpool opened as a centre for computer aided materials science, where robotic formulation, data capture, and modelling are being integrated into development practices.
[src:industry-4-0/industry-4-0] Industry 5.0 has been proposed as a strategy to create a paradigm shift for an industrial landscape in which the primary focus should no longer be on increasing efficiency, but rather on promoting the well-being of society and sustainability of the economy and industrial production.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] The broad definition of smart manufacturing covers many different technologies.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Some of the key technologies in the smart manufacturing movement include big data processing capabilities, industrial connectivity devices and services, and advanced robotics.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Smart manufacturing leverages big data analytics to optimize complex production processes and enhance supply chain management.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Big data analytics refers to a method for gathering and understanding large data sets in terms of what are known as the three V's, velocity, variety and volume.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Velocity informs the frequency of data acquisition, which can be concurrent with the application of previous data.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Variety describes the different types of data that may be handled.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Big data analytics allows an enterprise to use smart manufacturing to predict demand and the need for design changes rather than reacting to orders placed.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Some products have embedded sensors, which produce large amounts of data that can be used to understand consumer behavior and improve future versions of the product.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] One projected valuable element of big data processing is the introduction of and the ongoing progression to full supply chain autonomy.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Supply chain autonomy is an emerging concept in operations and logistics that describes supply chains capable of functioning independently, with minimal to no human input, by leveraging data.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Autonomous supply chains (ASCs) may be defined as systems that can self-manage across various functions, including planning, coordination, and execution, and the degree and inclusion of autonomy across these vectors defines the progression towards full autonomy.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Advanced industrial robots, also known as smart machines, operate autonomously and can communicate directly with manufacturing systems.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] In some advanced manufacturing contexts, they can work with humans for co-assembly tasks.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] By evaluating sensory input and distinguishing between different product configurations, these machines are able to solve problems and make decisions independent of people.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] These robots are able to complete work beyond what they were initially programmed to do and have artificial intelligence that allows them to learn from experience.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] These machines have the flexibility to be reconfigured and re-purposed.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] This gives them the ability to respond rapidly to design changes and innovation, which is a competitive advantage over more traditional manufacturing processes.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] An area of concern surrounding advanced robotics is the safety and well-being of the human workers who interact with robotic systems.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Traditionally, measures have been taken to segregate robots from the human workforce, but advances in robotic cognitive ability have opened up opportunities, such as cobots, for robots to work collaboratively with people.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Cloud computing allows large amounts of data storage or computational power to be rapidly applied to manufacturing, and allow a large amount of data on machine performance and output quality to be collected.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] This can improve machine configuration, predictive maintenance, and fault analysis.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Better predictions can facilitate better strategies for ordering raw materials or scheduling production runs.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] As of 2019, 3D printing is mainly used in rapid prototyping, design iteration, and small-scale production.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Improvements in speed, quality, and materials could make it useful in mass production and mass customization.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Smart manufacturing can also be attributed to surveying workplace inefficiencies and assisting in worker safety.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Efficiency optimization is a huge focus for adopters of "smart" systems, which is done through data research and intelligent learning automation.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] For instance operators can be given personal access cards with inbuilt Wi-Fi and Bluetooth, which can connect to the machines and a Cloud platform to determine which operator is working on which machine in real time.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] An intelligent, interconnected 'smart' system can be established to set a performance target, determine if the target is obtainable, and identify inefficiencies through failed or delayed performance targets.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] In general, automation may alleviate inefficiencies due to human error.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] And in general, evolving AI eliminates the inefficiencies of its predecessors.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] As robots take on more of the physical tasks of manufacturing, workers no longer need to be present and are exposed to fewer hazards.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Industry 4.0 is a project in the high-tech strategy of the German government that promotes the computerization of traditional industries such as manufacturing.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] The goal is the intelligent factory (Smart Factory) that is characterized by adaptability, resource efficiency, and ergonomics, as well as the integration of customers and business partners in business and value processes.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] Its technological foundation consists of cyber-physical systems and the Internet of Things.
[src:industry-4-0/smart-factory] European Roadmap "*Factories of the Future"* and German one "*Industrie 4.0″* illustrate several of the action lines to undertake and the related benefits.
